{{short description|A political ideology which advocates socialism based on the principles of Buddhism}} {{Socialism sidebar |expanded=Religious}}
'''Buddhist socialism''' is a [[political ideology]] which advocates [[socialism]] based on the principles of [[Buddhism]]. Both Buddhism and socialism seek to provide an end to suffering by analyzing its conditions and removing its main causes through [[praxis (process)|praxis]]. Both also seek to provide a transformation of personal consciousness (respectively, spiritual and political) to bring an end to human alienation and selfishness.<ref>Shields, James Mark; Liberation as Revolutionary Praxis: Rethinking Buddhist Materialism; Journal of Buddhist Ethics. Volume 20, 2013.</ref>
People who have been described as Buddhist socialists include [[Buddhadasa Bhikkhu]],<ref>Puntarigvivat, Tavivat (2003). [https://web.archive.org/web/20140613191428/http://www.stc.arts.chula.ac.th/CJBS/Buddhadasa%20Bhikkhu.pdf Buddhadasa Bhikkhu and Dhammic Socialism], The Chulalongkorn Journal of Buddhist Studies 2 (2), 189-207</ref><ref name="whatis">[http://www.suanmokkh.org/ds/what_ds1.htm What is Dhammic Socialism?] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100126045258/http://www.suanmokkh.org/ds/what_ds1.htm |date=January 26, 2010 }}</ref> [[B. R. Ambedkar]],<ref>Badal Sarkar, Dr. B.R. Ambedkar’s theory of State Socialism, International Research Journal of Social Sciences 2 (8), 38-41 (2013) [https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012636/http://www.isca.in/IJSS/Archive/v2/i8/6.ISCA-IRJSS-2013-113.pdf PDF]</ref> [[Han Yong-un]],<ref name="han">Tikhonov, Vladimir, Han Yongun's Buddhist Socialism in the 1920s-1930s, International Journal of Buddhist Thought and Culture 6, 207-228 (2006). [http://hompy.buddhapia.com/homepy/iabtc/files/Vol06_06_Vladimir%20Tikhonov.pdf PDF] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727075947/http://hompy.buddhapia.com/homepy/iabtc/files/Vol06_06_Vladimir%20Tikhonov.pdf |date=July 27, 2011 }}</ref> [[Seno’o Girō]],<ref>Shields, James Mark; Blueprint for Buddhist Revolution The Radical Buddhism of Seno’o Girō (1889–1961) and the Youth League for Revitalizing Buddhism, Japanese Journal of religious Studies 39 (2), 331-351 (2012) [https://web.archive.org/web/20131119194506/http://nirc.nanzan-u.ac.jp/nfile/4207 PDF]</ref> [[U Nu]] and [[Norodom Sihanouk]].<ref>[http://www.sjsu.edu/faculty/watkins/cambodia0.htm Cambodia Under the Khmer Rouge]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=4zlI-xIG1oEC&pg=PA216&lpg=PA216&dq=%22Norodom+Sihanouk%22+socialism&source=bl&ots=32XlEcJVAs&sig=I9mesJYUWAyDNZqSgEKErUaqWmM&hl=en&ei=ADy6TKOtPM-mnQeWn43ODQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CCgQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22Norodom%20Sihanouk%22%20socialism&f=false Monarchy in South-East Asia: the faces of tradition in transition]</ref>
Buddhadasa Bhikku coined the phrase "Dhammic socialism".<ref name="whatis"/> He believed that Socialism is a natural state meaning all things exist together in one system.<ref name="thought">Preecha Changkhwanyuen, [https://web.archive.org/web/20120313201742/http://www.stc.arts.chula.ac.th/CJBS/Dhammic%20Socialism.pdf Dhammic Socialism Political Thought of Buddhadasa Bhikku], Chulalangkorn Journal of Buddhist Studies 2 (1), page 118 (2003)</ref>
{{quote|Look at the birds: we will see that they eat only as much food as their stomachs can hold. They cannot take more than that; they don’t have granaries. Look down at the ants and insects: that is all they can do. Look at the trees: trees imbibe only as much nourishment and water as the trunk can hold, and cannot take in any more than that. Therefore a system in which people cannot encroach on each other’s rights or plunder their possessions is in accordance with nature and occurs naturally, and that is how it has become a society continued to be one, until trees became abundant, animals became abundant, and eventually human beings became abundant in the world. The freedom to hoard was tightly controlled by nature in the form of natural socialism.<ref name="thought"/>}}
Han Yong-un felt that equality was one of the main principles of Buddhism.<ref name="han"/> In an interview published in 1931, Yong-un spoke of his desire to explore Buddhist Socialism.
{{quote|I am recently planning to write about Buddhist socialism. Just like there is [[Christian socialism]] as a system of ideas in Christianity, there must be also Buddhist socialism in Buddhism.<ref name="han"/>}}
<!-- Image with inadequate rationale removed: [[File:Nehru and Gyatso 1959.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Jawaharlal Nehru]] and the Dalai Lama in [[Mussoorie]], at their first meeting after he fled Tibet in 1959.]] --> [[14th Dalai Lama|Tenzin Gyatso]], the Fourteenth [[Dalai Lama]] of Tibet has said that: {{quote|Of all the modern economic theories, the economic system of Marxism is founded on moral principles, while capitalism is concerned only with gain and profitability. (...) The failure of the regime in the former Soviet Union was, for me, not the failure of Marxism but the failure of totalitarianism. For this reason I still think of myself as half-Marxist, half-Buddhist.<ref>[http://hhdl.dharmakara.net/hhdlquotes1.html#marxism Tibet and China, Marxism, Nonviolence]</ref>}}
