The term '''Haziratu'l-Quds''' ([[Arabic]], ''sacred fold'') or '''Bahá'í centre''' refers to national, regional and local [[Bahá'í Faith|Bahá'í]] administrative centres.<ref name="momen">{{cite web | url = http://www.northill.demon.co.uk/relstud/hazirqud.htm | title = Haziratu'l-Quds | accessdate = 2007-03-20 | first = Moojan | last = Momen | authorlink = Moojan Momen | deadurl = yes | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070210171109/http://www.northill.demon.co.uk/relstud/hazirqud.htm | archivedate = 2007-02-10 | df = }}</ref>
[[Shoghi Effendi]], the head of the Bahá'í Faith in the first half of the 20th century, wrote that the Haziratu'l-Quds should include the [[wiktionary:secretariat|secretariat]], treasury, archives, library, publishing office, assembly hall, council chamber and the pilgrims' hostel. He also stated that its functions would be complementary to those of the [[Bahá'í House of Worship]], and that it would be desirable if both these buildings would be on the same site.<ref name="momen" /><ref>{{cite web | url = http://bahai-library.com/compilation_functions_importance_hazirat-quds| title = Functions and Importance of the Haziratu'l-Quds | accessdate = 2007-03-20 | last = Bahá'í World Centre| date = 1998-07-02}}</ref>
